{"cursor":"5461","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n at Arbat street, Moscow]]\n\nA 'post office', historically also a 'posthouse', A posthouse could also be\na place, in the days of post coaches, where relays of horses could be\nobtained is a facility forming part of a postal system for the posting,\nreceipt, sorting, handling, transmission or delivery of mail, such as letters,\nsmall packages, and usually money.\n\nPost offices offer mail-related services such as acceptance of mail and sale of\npostage stamps, post office boxes, and sale of packaging and stationery. In\naddition, some post offices offer non-postal services such as passport\napplications and other government forms, car tax purchase, money orders, and\nbanking services.\n\nA post office may have a main customer service and point of sale area. Many\npostal codes or ZIP codes route an item to a specific post office; some\ncorrespond to a specific route or even delivery point (business, residence, or\npost office box).\n\nIn a \"sorting office\" or \"delivery office\", mail is sorted or processed for\ndelivery. Large open spaces for sorting mail are also sometimes known as a\n'sorting hall' or 'postal hall'. Over time, sophisticated mail sorting and\ndelivery equipment has been developed, including Mail Rail.\n\n, Easter Island, Chile]] In Commonwealth countries, many of the larger post\noffice buildings in capital cities used the official title of General Post\nOffice. In parts of Europe, special Postal censorship offices were known as\nCabinets Noirs.\n\nAfter 1900, dedicated 'mail exchange' facilities became common and postal\nservices colocated customer services with businesses such as newsagents or\nrailway stations for the convenience of customers and to cut costs. As a result,\nmany purpose-built post offices became redundant and either fell into disuse or\nwere adaptively reused; sometimes retaining the title of Post Office prefixed by\nOld or Former for historical and heritage reasons.\n","linknr":245,"url":"Post_office","recorded":1374862764,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Post_office&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Post_office&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Post_Office_Ltd.","/wiki/Post_office_(disambiguation)","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f4/Ambox_content.png","/wiki/Talk:Post_office","/wiki/File:Pochtarossii-arbat.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d6/Pochtarossii-arbat.jpg/220px-Pochtarossii-arbat.jpg","/wiki/File:Pochtarossii-arbat.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Russian_Post","/wiki/Arbat","/wiki/Moscow","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Postal_system","/wiki/Mail","#cite_note-2","/wiki/Post_office_box","/wiki/Stationery","/wiki/Car_tax","/wiki/Money_order","/wiki/File:Postal_facility_interior.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/39/Postal_facility_interior.JPG/200px-Postal_facility_interior.JPG","/wiki/File:Postal_facility_interior.JPG","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Customer_service","/wiki/Point_of_sale","/wiki/Postal_code","/wiki/ZIP_code","/wiki/Mail_Rail","/wiki/File:Hanga_Roa_Post_Office.jpg","//up